      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Software QA procedures documented; version control and regression testing in place for CFD solver used in hemolysis prediction.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2) is a commercially validated code with documented QA processes. Version control records and regression test logs were reviewed and found compliant with Gradation 2 requirements. Achieved Gradation 3 due to additional in-house verification suite."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification against analytical or manufactured solutions for relevant flow regimes (laminar and turbulent rotating flow) at required gradation.",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification was performed using the method of manufactured solutions for laminar pipe flow and rotating cavity benchmarks. Results confirmed second-order spatial accuracy. Meets Gradation 2 requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Richardson extrapolation or equivalent GCI analysis performed on at least three systematically refined meshes; discretization error reported for hemolysis index QoI.",
      "rationale": "Three systematically refined meshes (2.1M, 6.8M, 18.4M elements) were generated and GCI analysis performed per Celik et al. (2008). GCI for normalized hemolysis index was 3.2% on the fine mesh, satisfying the Gradation 3 threshold. Mesh independence confirmed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions documented and traceable; boundary conditions in CFD model consistent with measured test conditions within stated uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "FDA pump bench test conditions (flow rates 2.5–6 L/min, rotational speeds 2000–3500 RPM) were documented with calibrated instrumentation. CFD boundary conditions set to match measured inlet velocity profiles and outlet pressure. Traceability confirmed at Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., E% or validation metric) computed for hemolysis index QoI; metric accounts for experimental uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) predicted by CFD compared to experimental measurements across 5 operating points. Mean absolute error was 8.4% with experimental uncertainty bands of ±12%. Validation metric computed per ASME V&V 20 framework. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation (NIH, shear stress distribution) are directly relevant to the COU decision quantity (relative hemolysis index RH).",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis and volume-averaged shear stress scalar are the primary QoIs. Both are directly linked to the RH acceptance criterion. The mapping from CFD QoI to clinical decision quantity is documented and reviewed. Gradation 2 met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments performed on geometry and operating conditions sufficiently representative of the COU geometry and operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation was performed on the FDA benchmark centrifugal pump geometry under CPB-representative flow conditions. The COU device shares the same impeller topology and operating envelope. Similarity analysis documented. Gradation 3 achieved due to direct geometric correspondence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence criteria documented; residuals and QoI monitors demonstrate solution convergence to required tolerance.",
      "rationale": "All simulations run to RMS residuals below 1e-5 with QoI monitors (NIH, torque) stabilized to within 0.1% over the final 200 iterations. Convergence plots archived. Gradation 2 requirements met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model and hemolysis damage model selection justified with reference to literature evidence and sensitivity analysis for the flow regime of interest.",
      "rationale": "SST k-omega turbulence model selected based on published benchmark studies for rotating blood-contacting devices. Hemolysis power-law damage model (Giersiepen et al.) evaluated against three alternative formulations in sensitivity study; NIH variation less than 5% across models at operating points of interest. Gradation 3 met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Blood rheological properties, geometric tolerances, and boundary condition uncertainties characterized and propagated through model to quantify input uncertainty contribution to QoI.",
      "rationale": "Blood viscosity (Newtonian assumption, mu=0.0035 Pa·s) and density (1060 kg/m³) assigned with literature-based uncertainty bounds. Geometric tolerance sensitivity study performed for impeller tip clearance (±0.05 mm). Combined input uncertainty contribution to NIH estimated at ±6.1%. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Assessment of potential use errors in model setup, execution, and post-processing that could affect QoI reliability.",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment was considered beyond the scope of the current submission. The analysis team noted that a formal use error review would require independent re-execution of the simulation workflow, which was not resourced within the project timeline. This factor is carried as not-assessed pending a planned follow-on review activity."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Characterization of test sample variability (device-to-device geometric variation, blood sample variability) and its influence on validation data representativeness.",
      "rationale": "Test sample characterization was considered outside the scope of the current credibility assessment. The validation dataset was sourced from published FDA benchmark studies where sample-level metadata was not fully available to the assessment team. A dedicated sample variability analysis is deferred to a future assessment cycle."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Demonstration that input parameters used in validation simulations are equivalent to those applicable in the COU, accounting for differences in geometry, operating conditions, and fluid properties.",
      "rationale": "Formal equivalency mapping between validation model inputs and COU-specific inputs was not completed within the current assessment scope. The team considered this factor to be addressed implicitly through the relevance-of-validation-activities assessment, but a standalone equivalency analysis was not documented. Deferred as beyond current scope."
    }
  ],
